Scientific analysis of the brass (or "bronze") used to make the famous Benin plaques and other
sculptures found that, beginning in the late 15th century, the metal (previously thought to have
come from the Netherlands) began to derive from the Rhineland region of Germany. At that time, the
brass was exported from Germany in the form of ring-shaped ingots which were used as currency in the
trans-Atlantic slave trade (bought from the Portuguese and incorporated by the people in Benin as a
metal source in sculpture), and subsequently melted down in Benin to produce Benin Bronzes.

